NATURAL LANGUAGE PROCESSING PROJECT¶

Executive Summary¶

The provided dataset contained 1176 text files (books) to be analyzed. A directory containing all the text files in a folder was set up to load all the text files. A dataframe was created and iterated through all the text files in the folder to extract the metadata about the books (File Name, Title, Author, Release Date, Release Year, Language) and the actual Text contained. The dataframe was divided into two other dataframes, one containing metadata and other containing only the text data from the files. Dataframe containing the text data was used for NLP type analysis using nltk library. Detailed analysis is divided into various sections of this report. The first 100 text files were used for the analysis considering the specifications of laptop. The dataframe was cleaned and words were tokenized before performing Exploratory Data Analysis. Various calculation and graphs were plotted to draw conclusions. POS tagging was done and number of unique POS tags for each file was calculated. Stemming and Lemmatization was performed to find the base words, and "wordnet" was used to find the synsets of words. Finally, Sentiment Analysis was performed to find the polarity scores.

As per the analysis, most frequent used words, Author who wrote the maximum books, Authors having highest/lowest Lexical Diversities, highest/lowest % of long words, highest polarity scores, and most/least number of Unique POS tags have been found. To conclude, few suggestions have been presented as an extension of this assignment with justifications in order to enrich the dataset with additional data and apply some additional advanced modelling and analysis.

# A Function is created to read the files from the current working dataset, extract the metadata and entire text in a dictionary
# The dictionary is returned as this function's output
# Code adopted from: https://medium.com/nerd-for-tech/the-gutenberg-project-natural-language-processing-1fc77616b298
# Many necessary modifications have been made to the adopted code

def read_and_clean(filepath, name):     # This will take the path and file name as arguments
    filepath = filepath + "\\" + name   # The path will be concatenated with the file name
    with open(filepath, 'r') as f:      # Opening the file using open function in "read" mode
        data = f.readlines()            # Reading the text document and storing it in "data" object
    data_dict = {"File_name":name,      # A dictionary is created with the mentioned columns, file name is passed directly 
                 "Title":None,          # Other variables are set as "None" since no information is available presently
                 "Author":None,
                 "Release_date":None,
                 "Release_year":None,
                 "Language":None,
                 "Text":None}  
    
    details = data[:1000]               # It was observed that the metadata of all the text documents was within first 1000
                                        # characters, hence a new variable "details" was created to iterate through first 1000 
    for i in details:                   # characters to extract the metadata about individual books.
        text = i.strip()                # Removing any leading or trailing spaces from the text

        if i.startswith("Title:") and data_dict["Title"] == None:    # If the text starts with "Title", extracting its matched
            title = text.split(":")[-1].strip()                      # content by using slicing
            data_dict["Title"] = title                               # The title is stored in the dictionary created above
        if i.startswith("Author:") and data_dict["Author"] == None:  # Same is repeated for all the metadata variables of books
            author = text.split(":")[-1].strip()
            data_dict["Author"] = author
        if i.startswith("Release Date:") and  data_dict["Release_date"] == None:    # Book Release date is extracted and split 
            date = text.split(":")[-1].strip()                                      # into Release date and Release year
            date = date.split("[")[0].strip()
            data_dict["Release_date"] = date
            data_dict["Release_year"] = date.split(",")[-1].strip()
        if i.startswith("Language:") and data_dict["Language"] == None:
            language = text.split(":")[-1].strip()
            data_dict["Language"] = language            
        
    text = " ".join([x.strip() for x in data])                       # text is extracted by iterating through the entire data   
    
    data_dict["Text"] = text                                         # The entire text is stored in the created dictionary 
    
    return data_dict                                                 # The dictionary is returned by the function as output

3. Cleaning the Data¶

  • Removing newlines, punctuations/special characters and converting to lowercase
In [24]:
# This function is created to clean the data by converting the strings to lowercase, removing unwanted characters 
# Code adopted from: 
  # 1. https://stackoverflow.com/questions/55187374/cleaning-text-with-python-and-re
  # 2. https://medium.com/@yashj302/text-cleaning-using-regex-python-f1dded1ac5bd

def remove_punctuation(text):                 # The function will accept the text from the dataframe
    text = str(text).lower()                  # Converting the text to lowercase
    text = re.sub('\[.*?\]', '', text)        # Removing all unwanted characters/special characters using Regular Expressions
    text = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', text)
    text = text.replace(os.linesep, "")
    text = re.sub(r'[0-9]', '', text)
    text = re.sub('https?://\S+', '', text)
    text = re.sub('<.*?>+', '', text)
    text = re.sub('\n', '', text)
    text = re.sub('\w*\d\w*', '', text)
    punctuationfree = "".join([i for i in text if i not in string.punctuation])  # Using the string.punctuation function to
                                                                                 # remove the punctuations from the text 
    
    return text                                                                  # Returning the clean text as function output

4. Tokenization¶

  • Tokenization means the separation of data, most often text into segments, and classification of those segments or labelling.
  • When used in NLP, it is a part of lexical analysis.
  • The main purpose of Tokenization is to convey information to the computer that humans can easily infer from the context and meaning of each word.

1. Word Frequency, Unique Words, Lexical Diversity and Hapaxes¶

The following is calculated:

  • The number of words, number of unique words and lexical diversity of a single book in the dataset
  • This is then applied to the entire dataset to get the Number of Words, Number of Unique Words, Lexical Diversity and Number of Hapaxes of all the 100 books

The Lexical Diversity is measured as the ratio of number of unique words to the total number of words

Hapaxes are the words that only appear once in a text

# This function is created to return the number of unique words in a text
# Code adopted from: 
  # https://stackoverflow.com/questions/53311151/function-that-calculates-the-total-number-of-unique-words-in-a-textfile

def Count_unique_words(text):                # Function accepts the text
    words = str(text)                        # Converting it into a continuous string
    uniqueWords = set(words.split())         # Splitting the string into words and filtering only unique words using set
    return len(uniqueWords)                  # Returning the number of unique words
In [32]:
# This function is created to return the number of hapaxes in a text
# Code adopted from the module's lecture video/exercises 

def n_hapaxes(text):                                         # Function accepts the text
    nltk_words = nltk.tokenize.word_tokenize(str(text))      # Converts the text into string and then create word tokens
    fdist = FreqDist(nltk_words)                             # Counting the frequency of words
    n_hapaxes = len(fdist.hapaxes())                         # Finding only the number of hapaxes words (that only occur once)
    return n_hapaxes                                         # Returning the number of hapaxes

lex_div = n_unique/n_words             # Calculating the Lexical Diversity of book1 & returning the same (Unique/Total words)
n_hap = n_hapaxes(book1)               # Returning the number of hapaxes in book 1

print(f'1. Book1 contains {n_words} Words')
print(f'2. There are {n_unique} Unique Words in Book1')
print(f'3. The Lexical Diversity of Book1 is {lex_div}')
print(f'4. There are {n_hap} Hapaxes in Book1')

1. Book1 contains 72093 Words
2. There are 2068 Unique Words in Book1
3. The Lexical Diversity of Book1 is 0.0286851705436034

2. Frequency Distribution of Words (With and without Stopwords)¶

The following is done:

  • Bar graph has been created to see the 10 Most frequently used Words in the dataset including Stopwords
  • A new column has been created in the dataframe to store the words after removing the stopwords
  • Bar graph has been created to see the 10 Most frequently used Words in the dataset after removing the stopwords

Stopwords are words that are so prevalent that standard tokenizers essentially ignore them, such as "a," "an," "the," "of," "in," etc.

These stopwords carry very little information as they does not convey meaning in the context the of semantics of the text

In [44]:

most_freq_words = []                         # An empty list is created to store the most frequent Words
for i in data_explore["Tokenized_word"]:     # Iterating through the column "Tokenized_word" which contains words for all text files
    for word in i:                           # Iterating through each file

# This function will give the list removing all the stopwords present in the nltk library for English language

def remove_stopwords(text):                                             # The function will accept the text
    no_stopwords = [word for word in text if word not in stop_words]    # Iterating through all the words that are not in stopwords
    return no_stopwords                                                 # Returning words excluding stopwords

3. Longwords¶

  • An assumption is made that the words greater than 10 characters are long words
  • Using this, number of long words and % of long words in each text file is calculated
In [51]:
# This function will return the number of long words present in a text
# Code adopted from: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q7AM9QjCRrI&list=PLUCTTwyv9AdUYtNeV5w-2xMX5O9cCcfkB&index=5

def long_words(text):                               # Function will accept text as argument
    long_word = [w for w in text if len(w) > 10]    # Looping through all the words in text, checking if word length is > 10
    n = len(long_word)                              # If length of word is > 10, it is returned by the function
    return n                                        # Number of long words is returned as function output

# This function will create bigrams of words from the text file

def create_bigrams(text):                          # Function will accept the text
    bigram_words = [word for word in text]         # The words will be passed into a list through iteration
    bigrams = list(nltk.bigrams(bigram_words))     # "bigrams" function of nltk library is used to create lists of word bigrams
    return bigrams                                 # bigrams of words will be returned as a list

# This function will return the number of unique POS tags from a text file

def unique_pos_tags(text):                     # Function will accept text as argument
    just_the_tags = [tu[1] for tu in text]     # Iterating through the text, and getting second elememts (Tags) of the tuple
    n_unique_tags = len(set(just_the_tags))    # Finding the length of the unique tags present in the dataset
    return n_unique_tags                       # Function will return the number of unique POS tags

7. Word Cloud¶

  • A Word Cloud has been generated for a selected book from the dataframe

A Word Cloud is a visual representation of text data in the form of tags, which are typically single words whose importance is visualised by way of their size and color.

A Word Cloud is an good option to help visually interpret text and is useful in quickly gaining insight into the most occuring words in a given text, by visualizing the word frequency in the text.

In [62]:
# This function will generate the word cloud for any given book in the dataframe
# Code adopted from: 
  # 1. https://neptune.ai/blog/exploratory-data-analysis-natural-language-processing-tools
  # 2. https://github.com/MengyaoHuang/Data-Manipulation-and-Analysis/blob/master/Natural%20Language%20Processing%20for%20Project%20Gutenberg.ipynb  

def book_word_cloud(text):                                  # Function will accept the text as argument
    
    words_in_cloud = " ".join(word for word in text)        # Iterating through the text and joining the words
    stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)                              # Creating a set of unique stopwords to exclude from the word cloud
    word_cloud = WordCloud(stopwords = stopwords, background_color = "white").generate(words_in_cloud)    # Generating word cloud
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,8))
    plt.imshow(word_cloud, interpolation = "bilinear")
    plt.title("Word Cloud of the selected Book", size = 20, fontweight = "bold")
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.show()

8. Stemming and Lemmatization¶

Stemming and Lemmarization are processes of word normalisation, removing conflations and converting each word to its base form.

It is a pre-processing stage that is recommended to take place before any automated analysis or process, because without it most Machine Learning algorithms would struggle to find any patterns in the text being analysed since there will be too many variations of each word in the text and therefore too much noise.

8.1 Stemming¶

Stemming is the process of cutting off letters until the user ends up with some base form of the word.

The Stemming algorithms usually remove comon suffixes and prefixes, along with definite articles in languages that have them attached to the word.

In [64]:

8.2 Lemmatization¶

Lemmatisation on the other hand, will produce the actual words because it converts the original words into their linguistic base, removing any indication of variation based on time or quantity.

This means that the results will have the same basic meaning just in its root form.

In [66]:
# WordNetLemmatizer is used to perform lemmatization of words

lemmer = WordNetLemmatizer()      # Creating an object "lemmer" of WordNetLemmatizer
  • The wordnet is used because the lemmatizer relies on knowing, to what part of speech words belong, to lemmatize according to the filemap.
  • So the wordnet lemmatizer only works for nouns, verbs, adjectives and adverbs.
In [67]:
display(wn._FILEMAP)

{'a': 'adj', 'r': 'adv', 'n': 'noun', 'v': 'verb'}
  • This information has to be passed to lemmatizer for each word as the key in this filemap
  • However there are two issues when using POS_tag function:
    • There are many more tags than the lemmatizer uses
    • And the tags have to be converted to one of the single character keys in the file map
In [68]:
# As a solution to this, a function is defined to make that conversion
# Since there are 4 possibilities, the get method will allow to define a default value that is chosen as a Noun,
# which is actually the default value for the wordnet lemmatizer if the tag is not passed
# Code adopted from the module's lectures/exercises

def get_file_key(pos_tag):
    return {"NN":"n",                
            "VB":"v",
            "RB":"r",
            "JJ":"a"
            }.get(pos_tag[:2],"n")

9. Wordnet¶

The following are generated using wordnet:

  • Synsets
  • Lemmas
  • Hyponyms
  • Hypernyms

Wordnet is a network of words.

Words are connected by a number of grammatical and semantical rules, synonymy being the main one, where words that mean the same thing are connected and grouped together.

In a wordnet, these groups are called Synsets.

The words and synsets are furthermore connected by connections called Hyponyms

As wordnet is a tree, one can get the node above a word with Hypernyms and all the branches below a word with Hyponyms

Lemma is a form of a word that appears as an entry in a dictionary and is used to represent all the other possible forms.

Since "said" and "man" were among the most frequent words in the dataset, these are explored further using wordnet

In [70]:
# Code adopted from the module's exercise

syn1 = wn.synsets("said")[0]                     # Defining a variable "syn1" to store the first synset of word "said"
syn2 = wn.synsets("man")[0]                      # Defining a variable "syn2" to store the first synset of word "man" 

for syns in [syn1,syn2]:                         # Iterating through the synsets of the given words
    print("Exploring", syns.name())              # Printing the Name of the synset
    print("Definition:",syns.definition())       # Printing the Definition of the synset
    print("Examples:",syns.examples())           # Printing the Examples of the synset
    print("Hyernyms:",syns.hypernyms())          # Printing the Hypernyms of the synset 
    print("Hyponyms:", syns.hyponyms())          # Printing the Hyponyms of the synset
    print("Lemmas:", syns.lemmas())              # Printing the Lemmas of the synset
    print("\n")                                  # A new line to separate the two synsets

10. Sentiment Analysis¶

  • A new dataframe containing the cleaned text has been created from previous dataframe to perform Sentiment Analysis
  • The text has been lemmatized and polarity scores for Positive, Negative and Neutral sentiments have been calculated using Sentiment Intensity Analyzer

Sentiment Analysis is used for identifying, extracting, and quantifying sentimental information from the text.

There are multiple types of sentiment analysis and the basic one is to classify the polarity of the text document (Negative, Positive or Neutral).

Question 1: Who are the Authors and their Books with the highest Lexical Diversity and lowest Lexical Diversity?¶

Justification of why this question is interesting¶

  • This will provide insights about the Authors and their Books with the highest and lowest Lexical Richness
  • Lexical diversity can assist in assessing the text complexity in the book and, consequently, how challenging or easy it is to read for both native speakers and non-native speakers, as well as the author's probable linguistic proficiency.

Question 2: Who are the Authors with the most Positive, Negative and Neutral attitude towards writing their books measured using Polarity Scores?¶

  • The Author and Book are identified using the ID that has the books with the highest Positive, Negative and Neutral polarity scores

Justification of why this question is interesting¶

  • The main goal of sentiment analysis is to examine a body of text in order to comprehend the opinion it expresses.
  • Polarity is the overall attitude that a book or a text conveys.
  • A "sentiment score" is a numerical evaluation that captures this polarity.
  • Typically, this sentiment is measured by assigning it a polarity - a positive, negative or a neutral value.
  • The sign of the polarity score is frequently used to infer whether the overall sentiment is positive, neutral, or negative.
  • This can provide insights about the orientation of the Authors

  • (b) the genre of the book and the publication
  • (c) the reader/user details like age, location
  • (d) the average book ratings by users
  • (e) the count of ratings by users
  • (f) the count of text reviews

A Book Recommender System can be built using Machine Learning techniques where books can be classified based on user needs.
The recommender system can suggest books to a user by comparing the user-liked or highly rated books with the unrated or low rated books, possibly looking for the most appropriate content to suggest.

There are many datasets corresponding to book reviews and ratings from website called Goodreads(https://www.goodreads.com) that enables users to search through its library of books, authors, ratings, and reviews.

These datasets can be found from any of the following open source databases:

  • (a) https://www.kaggle.com
  • (b) https://sites.google.com/eng.ucsd.edu/ucsdbookgraph

Book IDs (ISBN) can be fetched by searching through the book titles. Using that, a list of book that the user likes can be created to recommend the book that the user has not read yet and might like based on all of these factors in the dataset.

A table can be created to map out the users who did not read a book. The program can request the books ID from the user before internally calculating its correlation with the other books in the dataset. Then the correlation scores can be used to determine which book should be recommended.

The program can also select the users, books, and associated features to present the recommendation using multiclassification or regression techniques. Recommendation can be based on choosing the best rated books as determined by the model.

Recommendation can also be done by finding all of the users who liked the same book as the user and finding all other books they liked, to use those as recommendations.

Suggestion 2. Using spaCy library, Shallow Parsing and Dependency Parsing can be done.¶

The process of breaking down a sentence into its simplest components (tokens such as words) and grouping them into higher-level phrases is known as Shallow Parsing or Chunking. It is a method of obtaining short phrases meaningfully from sentences that have been identified as parts of speech. Words comprises of chunks, and the POS tags are used to define the types of words.

Shallow Parsing employs POS tags as inputs and outputs chunks, building on top of POS tagging. There is a standard set of chunk tags, similar to POS tags (such as Noun Phrase (NP) or Verb Phrase (VP)). This is a crucial step  when information like location or a person's name needs to be extracted from text in a process known as Named Entity Recognition (NER).

Dependency Parsing is the process of analysing a sentence's grammatical structure to identify related words and the nature of their relationships. Every relationship consists of a head and a dependent that influences the head. Each relationship is given a classification based on the nature of the dependency between the head and dependent. The development of information extraction systems, Natural Language Understanding systems, and text pre-processing for deep learning systems can all incorporate this technique.

These two parsing techniques can be built as an extension to POS tagging done in this assignment.

Referred from:

  • (b) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kyU1yZab4yA
  • (c) https://www.tutorialspoint.com/natural_language_toolkit/natural_language_toolkit_parsing.htm

Suggestion 3. Named Entity Recognition can be done as an extension of this project.¶

There are special terms that represent particular entities that are more informative and have a specific context in any text. Named entities are phrases that reflect real-world items like people, locations, organisations, and so forth, which are identified by proper names.

Named entity recognition (NER), can be used for identifying and classifying named entities into a variety of predetermined categories as an advancement to this assignment.

The tokens or chunks extracted during Shallow Parsing can be searched against a knowledge base, which is an ontology consisting of words, their meanings, and the relationships among these words.
